Introduction
************

Many applications are written for UMS til now. In order that every
program does not have its own way of invocation, especially the
programs with a graphical user interface (GUI), the UMS developer guild
came to terms to create a guideline to standardize the manner of
starting UMS applications.


@EndNode

@Node "General" "loginguide.guide/General"
@Next "Shell Startup"
@Prev "Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

General
*******

An application should take into account the command line arguments
(Shell) respectively Workbench tooltypes @{i}NAME@{ui}, @{i}PASSWORD@{ui} and @{i}SERVER@{ui}.
Concerning invocation from a Shell, the order of arguments should match
above example, with @{i}SERVER@{ui} declared a keyword. This results in a
command template beginning @{b}UMSapp NAME,PASSWORD,SERVER/K[,...]@{ub} (@{b}UMSapp@{ub}
means the name of the application).


@EndNode

@Node "Shell Startup" "loginguide.guide/Shell Startup"
@Next "GUI Login"
@Prev "General"
@Toc "Main"

Application startup from Shell
******************************

If the application is passed a questionmark as the only argument on the
command line (i.e. @{b}UMSapp ?@{ub}), it should return the template to StdOut
and offer a prompt to have the user enter the desired options.

   Example:
     1> @{b}UMSapp ?@{ub}
     NAME/A,PASSWORD,SERVER/K,OPTION/F:

The user should be able to request additional help by responding to the
prompt with another questionmark. Additional help consists of complete
version information (at least a standard version template as specified
in `Amiga User Interface Styleguide' (pp. 110)) accompanied by short
help information.

   Example:
     1> @{b}UMSprog ?@{ub}
     NAME/A,PASSWORD,SERVER/K,OPTION1/K,SWITCH/S: @{b}?@{ub}
     
     $VER: UMSprog 1.0 (30.02.93)
     (C)1993 by Joe Fake
     
     Log into UMS message base and then log out
     OPTION1: Stay <OPTION1> secs in message base
     SWITCH:  Don't log in, but print "Hello"
     
     Usage:
     UMSprog NAME/A,PASSWORD,SERVER/K,OPTION1/K,SWITCH/S
     
     Default: OPTION1=10
     :


 @{" Technical Realisation " Link "Technical Realisation"}        How to program ...


@EndNode

@Node "Technical Realisation" "loginguide.guide/Technical Realisation"
@Prev "Shell Startup"
@Toc "Shell Startup"

Technical Realisation
=====================

@{b}DOS.ReadArgs()@{ub} provides a standard means to parsing the command line
and behaves exactly in the above described manner (it should therefore
be used). Additional help text can be passed to @{b}ReadArgs()@{ub} by supplying
a custom @{b}RDArgs@{ub} structure as third argument which holds a pointer to
the text string in @{b}RDA_ExtHelp@{ub}. Refer to `The AmigaDOS Manual', Chapter
5, Basic Input and Output Programming, Standard Command Line Parsing
(pp. 181 as of the 3rd edition).


@EndNode

@Node "GUI Login" "loginguide.guide/GUI Login"
@Next "Authors"
@Prev "Shell Startup"
@Toc "Main"

Application startup Via GUI
***************************

If an application provides a login requester, it should act as follows:

   If @{i}NAME@{ui} is not specified at startup time, it must be entered to the
login requester. Activate the name object.

   It is legal to pass an empty @{i}PASSWORD@{ui} as long as a name is
specified.  Thus the empty password must attempt a login! If the user
passes the period (".") as @{i}PASSWORD@{ui}, she desires to enter her password
to the login requester. It should open with the password object
activated.

   If there is no @{i}SERVER@{ui} specified and the login requester must be
opened due to the above guidelines, the server object should be filled
with the name of the default server (i.e. the server to which the user
would be going to log into if she was not naming a different one
herself). The default server's name can be read from the ENV
@{i}$UMSSERVER@{ui}. If the ENV does not exist, the default name is
"default". :-)

   This is an simplified example of a login requester:
      ________________________
     |.|_UMSapp:_login______|I|
     |            __________  |
     | Name:     |Joe_Fake__| |
     |            __________  |
     | Password: |*****_____| |
     |            __________  |
     | Server:   |default___| |
     |________________________|
     |    ____      ______    |
     |   |_OK_|    |Cancel|  _|
     |______________________|/|

A failed GUI login should be answered in a requester. After confirmation
the user should be presented with the unmodified login requester again
as to correct her wrong inputs. Cancelling the requester should result
in terminating the application.


@EndNode

